The main analysis was a 2 (condition: mortality salience vs.
control priming task) × 2 (ethnicity: European American vs. Asian American) univariate ANOVAs
on the dependent variable of the Prostitution Attitudes Scale scores, which yielded a significant
interactive effect on PAS (Prostitution Attitudes Scale) score, F(1, 38) = 10.263, p = .003

[HYPOTHESIS]
That there will be an interaction effect between ethnicity (European American vs. Asian American) and priming condition (mortality salience vs. pain control task) on participants’ Prostitution Attitudes Scale scores, such that after mortality salience, Asian American participants will show more positive attitudes toward prostitution and European American participants will show less positive attitudes toward prostitution in the mortality salience condition than in the control condition.
